  "prompt": "How do microeconomics and macroeconomics differ?",
  "response": "Microeconomics and macroeconomics differ in several key ways:\n\n1. Scope of Analysis\n- Microeconomics: Focuses on individual economic units like consumers, firms, and specific markets\n- Macroeconomics: Examines the economy as a whole, including national and global economic trends\n\n2. Key Areas of Study\n- Microeconomics: Price determination, consumer behavior, firm production, market structures\n- Macroeconomics: Inflation, unemployment, economic growth, monetary and fiscal policies\n\n3. Level of Observation\n- Microeconomics: Specific markets and individual economic agents\n- Macroeconomics: Aggregate economic indicators and broad economic performance\n\n4. Primary Questions\n- Microeconomics: How do individual consumers and firms make decisions?\n- Macroeconomics: How do overall economic conditions function and interact?\n\n5. Key Concepts\n- Microeconomics: Supply and demand, opportunity cost, market equilibrium\n- Macroeconomics: GDP, national income, monetary policy, fiscal policy\n\n6. Analytical Tools\n- Microeconomics: Supply/demand curves, marginal analysis\n- Macroeconomics: Aggregate economic models, national accounting\n\nBoth fields are interconnected and essential for understanding economic systems comprehensively.",
